# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ants-climbing-a-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/a-gei] The ageh was reportedly created in 1965 by Iông-tēⁿ Gím-bûn (楊鄭錦文), who combined various food items sold at her Chin-lí street (真理街) food stall to sell as a new food item.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/a-gei] This original ageh consisted of fried tofu that has been emptied of its center, stuffed with cellophane noodles cooked in stewed ground pork, its opening sealed and covered with a carrot and surimi mixture, and then steamed to completion.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/a-gei] The dish incorporates several techniques from other dishes, including the stuffing of abura-age in the manner of *inarizushi*, the capping of tofu with surimi to make Yong Tau Foo, and the use of cellophane noodles as a filling for many stuffed pastries.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/a-gei] The individual a-gei are served with either a plain soy-based or a sweet chili sauce.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/a-gei] A-gei is commonly eaten with a bowl of stuffed fish ball soup in the winter and a glass of cold soy milk in the summer.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/aburasoba] Mazesoba was introduced in the 1950s, with Chinchintei opening up in Musashino City in the 1950s.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/aburasoba] The largest aburasoba chain in the world is Kokoro Mazesoba.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/aburasoba] There are two theories about its origin: one is that Sanko, a restaurant near Hitotsubashi University in Kunitachi City, founded in 1952, started serving it as a snack with alcohol.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/aburasoba] They were likely inspired in the 1950s by soggy ramen noodles.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/aburasoba] The other theory is that Chinchintei, a restaurant near Asia University in the Musashino City district, started selling aburasoba in the 1950s.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/aburasoba] It became popular and ranked in the Shimbun list of Trending Products of the Year.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/aburasoba] In 2002, Myojo Foods launched the "Bubukka" oil-based instant noodles in Kichijoji, Musashino City.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/aburasoba] It is said that it became popular among students because of its relatively low price and large portions.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/aburasoba] According to Great Gidayu, after entering Asia University, a senior student took him to a restaurant that served *aburasoba* as a "rite of passage".
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/aburasoba] Although he didn't think it tasted good at first, he became addicted after going there several times.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/aburasoba] Chinchintei sells noodles, soup, and more by mail order, but most of the orders are from alumni of Asia University.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/aburasoba] It has also become a specialty menu item at some student cafeterias.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Alton Brown was born July 30, 1962, in Los Angeles, California.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] His father, Alton Crawford Brown, was a media executive in Cleveland, Georgia; owner of radio station WRWH; and publisher of the newspaper *White County News*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] He died on Alton's last day of sixth grade from an apparent suicide.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown studied film at the University of Georgia in the early 1980s.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] He left the university in 1985 only one credit hour short of completing his bachelor's degree.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] He eventually received it in 2004 after learning that the university's Department of Theatre and Film had since reduced the number of required credits.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown got his start in television in the 1980s as a cinematographer for music videos, working on videos such as R.E.M.'s "The One I Love".
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In the 1990s, he became dissatisfied with the quality of cooking shows airing on American television, so he set out to produce his own show.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In preparation, Brown enrolled in the New England Culinary Institute, graduating in 1997.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] He says that he was a poor science student in high school and college, but Brown focused on the subject to understand the underlying processes of cooking.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] He is outspoken in his shows about his dislike of single-purpose kitchen utensils and equipment such as garlic presses and margarita machines, although Brown adapts a few traditionally single-purpose devices, such as rice cookers and melon ballers, into multipurpose tools.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The pilot for *Good Eats* first aired in July 1998 on the PBS member TV station WTTW in Chicago.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Food Network picked up the show in July 1999.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Many of the *Good Eats* episodes feature Brown building makeshift cooking devices in order to point out that many of the devices sold at conventional "cooking" stores are simply fancified hardware store items.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] *Good Eats* was nominated for the Best TV Food Journalism Award by the James Beard Foundation in 2000.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The show was also awarded a 2006 Peabody Award.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In May 2011, Alton Brown announced an end to *Good Eats* after 14 seasons.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The final episode, "Turn on the Dark", aired February 10, 2012.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] On Alton's 2017 book tour, he stated that *Good Eats* would have a sequel and that it would be released to the internet in 2018.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] This was changed in late 2018 when Brown made arrangements with The Cooking Channel to air "revised" versions of several episodes with new recipes titled *Good Eats Reloaded*, in which he stated new episodes of *Good Eats* are also in the works.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Thirteen episodes of *Good Eats Reloaded* aired in late winter and early spring 2019, and were added to the *Good Eats* reruns on The Cooking Channel.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] It was announced on June 5, 2019, that the new show would be called *Good Eats Returns*; it premiered on the Food Network with the slightly revised title *Good Eats: The Return* on Sunday, August 25.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown relaunched the show in two versions: as *Good Eats Reloaded* on Cooking Channel (which updates, reworks and adds to original *Good Eats* episodes), and on Food Network as *Good Eats: The Return* in August 2019 (all-new episodes).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] New episodes of *Reloaded* premiered in April 2020.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] New *Return* episodes were in the writing process and planned to be filming over the summer of 2020, but were delayed due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] These episodes eventually saw release, initially as an exclusive on the new Discovery+ streaming service.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In June 2021, the episodes premiered on Food Network as a companion to the *Chopped: Alton's Maniacal Baskets* tournament.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] On July 13, 2021, Brown announced that *Good Eats: The Return* would not be returning for a third season.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] A third planned season of *Good Eats Reloaded* was also cancelled, but the recipes planned for the series were included as part of Brown's *"Good Eats 4: The Final Years"* cookbook.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In 2004, Brown appeared on *Iron Chef America: Battle of the Masters*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] This was the second attempt to adapt the Japanese cooking show *Iron Chef* to American television (the first being UPN's *Iron Chef USA*, which featured William Shatner).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown served as the expert commentator, a modified version of the role played by Dr.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] When the show became a series, Brown began serving as the play-by-play announcer, with Kevin Brauch as kitchen reporter.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown also served as the host for all five seasons of the spin-off *The Next Iron Chef*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown's third series, *Feasting on Asphalt*, explores the history of eating on the move.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown and his crew traveled around the United States via motorcycle in a four-part miniseries about the history of road food.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown samples food all along his travel route.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] He includes a "history of food" segment documenting famous road trips and interviews many of the foodies he meets en route.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The series premiered on Food Network on July 29, 2006.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The miniseries was picked up for a second run, *Feasting on Asphalt 2: The River Run*, in 2007.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Six episodes were filmed between April and May 2007.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The episodes trace the majority of the length of the Mississippi River through Brown's travels.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The second run of episodes began airing on Food Network on August 4, 2007.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The third season uses the title *Feasting on Waves* and has Brown traveling the Caribbean by boat in search of local cuisine.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In 2013, Brown began hosting the cooking competition series *Cutthroat Kitchen* on the Food Network.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In each episode, four chefs are each given $25,000 with which to bid on items that can be used to hinder their opponents' cooking, such as confiscating ingredients or forcing them to use unorthodox tools and equipment.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Three chefs are eliminated one by one, and the winner keeps their unspent money as the day's prize.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The series premiered on August 11, 2013.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In 2018, Brown hosted Season 18 of *Worst Cooks in America* as the blue team mentor.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In 2022, Netflix rebooted *Iron Chef America* as *Iron Chef: Quest for an Iron Legend*, signing Brown as co-host with Kristen Kish.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In October 2013, Brown launched Alton Brown Live: The Edible Inevitable Tour, his first national tour visiting 46 cities through March 2014.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The show included stand-up comedy, talk show antics, a multimedia lecture, live music, and "extreme" food experimentation.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] After a hiatus of several months while Brown worked on his Food Network shows, the tour resumed in October 2014 and concluded on April 4, 2015, in Houston, Texas, after visiting more than 60 cities.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown mounted a second tour show, Alton Brown Live: Eat Your Science, in 2016.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The show toured through the fall of 2017.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] All totaled, Brown's shows have played over 225 dates including Broadway.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Both his tours have included "large, unusual and probably dangerous" food demonstrations, audience participation, and even food songs performed by Brown and his combo.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown has been quoted as saying his final tour will launch in the fall of 2020.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown's third tour titled Alton Brown Live: Beyond the Eats was announced on his Twitter page in March 2021.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The tour began in October 2021 and had several "legs" or overall tour runs, the last of which (done with added "holiday" materials) ran from November to December 2024.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown is the recipient of two James Beard Awards.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] He won the Best Book award in 2003 for his first book, *I'm Just Here for the Food*, and the Broadcast Media Award in 2011 for TV Food Personality/Host.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] He has also been nominated four additional times.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown served as a mentor on Season 8 of *The Next Food Network Star* alongside Bobby Flay and Giada De Laurentiis.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] During Season 8, each mentor selected and mentored a team of five finalists.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Alton's finalist, Justin Warner, was the Season 8 winner; however, Brown will not be producing Warner's show.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown guest-starred in an episode of *SpongeBob SquarePants* titled "House Fancy" where he provides the voice of Nicholas Withers, the host of the titular show.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown appeared on the Travel Channel show *The Layover* with Anthony Bourdain which focused on the city of Atlanta in 2013.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In the episode Bourdain takes Brown to the Clermont Lounge.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown guest starred as the "Guest Bailiff" and "Expert Witness" in John Hodgman's comedy/court show podcast *Judge John Hodgman*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In October 2017, Brown was featured on the Food Network television show *Chopped* in a five-part series called "Alton Brown's Challenge".
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown voiced Yum Labouché in *Big Hero 6: The Series*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The character is a judge for an underground cooking competition.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown appeared on episode 196 of *MythBusters* titled "Food Fables".
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In June 2022, he appeared on the web series *Good Mythical Morning* episode "Match the Flavor to the Doritos".
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] He was originally scheduled to appear in a summer 2020 episode, as he revealed in a livestream in March 2020, however did not happen due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown has done commercial work for General Electric products, including five infomercials touting the benefits of GE refrigerators, washers and dryers, water purifiers, Trivection ovens, and dishwashers.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The infomercials are produced in the *Good Eats* style, employing the use of unusual camera angles, informational text, props, visual aids, scientific explanations, and the same method of delivery.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] These infomercials are distributed to wholesale distributors of appliances/plumbing devices.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown has also aided GE in developing a new type of oven.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] He was initially called by GE to help their engineers learn more about the effects of heat on food; that grew into an active cooperation to develop GE's Trivection oven.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown has promoted Colgate toothpaste, Dannon yogurt, Welch's, Shun knives, and Heifer International.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In 2010, he endorsed kosher salt use in a campaign for Cargill.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In 2022, Brown began appearing in commercials and marketing campaigns for the supplement Neuriva.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In 2012, Brown gained popularity by pioneering the use of humorous "Analog Tweets", wherein he posts pictures of hand-written or drawn Twitter responses on Post-it Notes which he has stuck to his computer monitor.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] On June 28, 2013, Alton Brown joined the Nerdist Podcast Network with his podcast *The Alton Browncast*, covering food news, men's style, music and other topics.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] 68 episodes were produced from 2013 to 2017.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] With the COVID-19 quarantine in 2020 and the subsequent delays in production on Season 16 of *Good Eats* (Season 2 of "The Return"), Alton took to YouTube to make two new online cooking series.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In November, 2025, Alton started a new series on his YouTube channel called ***Alton Brown Cooks Food***.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Weekly episodes contain a mix of new recipes, cooking tips (e.g., on knife skills), updates of old recipes and techniques, and have featured popular YouTube guests such as Andrew Rea (of Binging with Babish) and Guga Foods.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The episodes sometimes contain moderately racy jokes, which is a departure from Alton's made-for-television productions.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] The episodes are shot at his private test kitchen, sound stage, and studio in Marietta, Georgia.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] He and his first wife DeAnna, an executive producer on *Good Eats*, divorced in 2015.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] They have one daughter, who was born in 1999.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] A few members of his extended family appeared on *Good Eats* (such as his late grandmother, his mother, and daughter, who is known on the show as "Alton's Spawn"), but most of his "family" portrayed on the series were actors or members of the show's production crew.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown and Atlanta restaurant designer Elizabeth Ingram became engaged in 2018.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown posted in September 2018 that he and Ingram had married on a boat in Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown was once a motorcycling enthusiast, although he no longer owns one.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown is also an airplane pilot and was featured in the aviation magazine *AOPA Flight Training*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] He owned two planes, a Cessna 206 and a Cessna 414.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown also collects vintage watches and wears a different one for every season of *Good Eats*; this was used in production to quickly identify which season a clip is from.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] When his watch broke midseason, Brown continued to wear it for the rest of the season to maintain this system.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Twenty years after the Omega Seamaster watch his father left him was stolen, Brown bought it from an eBay seller and had it restored.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown changed his eating habits in 2009 in order to lose weight and become healthier, losing 50 pounds (23 kg) over the course of nine months.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown discussed his Christian beliefs in a 2010 interview with *Eater*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] In November 2020, Brown declared on Twitter that he has almost always voted Republican, but that the 2016 United States Presidential Election was the first time he considered voting for a Democrat since Michael Dukakis in 1988.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Brown supported Joe Biden in the 2020 U.S.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/alton-brown] Presidential Election, as well as Democrats running in U.S.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ants form colonies that range in size from a few dozen individuals often living in small natural cavities to highly organised colonies that may occupy large territories with a sizeable nest (or nests) that consist of millions of individuals.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] In some cases they reach hundreds of millions of individuals in super colonies.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Typical colonies consist of various castes of sterile, wingless females, most of which are workers (ergates), as well as soldiers (dinergates) and other specialised groups.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Nearly all ant colonies also have some fertile males called "drones" and one or more fertile females called "queens" (gynes).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The colonies are described as superorganisms because the ants appear to operate as a unified entity, collectively working together to support the colony.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ants have colonised almost every landmass on Earth.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The only places lacking indigenous ants are Antarctica and a few remote or inhospitable islands.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ants thrive in moist tropical ecosystems and may exceed the combined biomass of wild birds and mammals.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Their success in so many environments has been attributed to their social organisation and their ability to modify habitats, tap resources, and defend themselves.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Their long co-evolution with other species has led to mimetic, commensal, parasitic, and mutualistic relationships.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ant societies have division of labour, communication between individuals, and an ability to solve complex problems.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] These parallels with human societies have long been an inspiration and subject of study.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Many human cultures make use of ants in cuisine, medication, and rites.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Some species are valued in their role as biological pest control agents.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Their ability to exploit resources may bring ants into conflict with humans, however, as they can damage crops and invade buildings.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Some species, such as the red imported fire ant (*Solenopsis invicta*) of South America, are regarded as invasive species in other parts of the world, establishing themselves in areas where they have been introduced accidentally.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The word *ant* and the archaic word *emmet* are derived from **ante**, **emete** of Middle English, which come from **ǣmette** of Old English; these are all related to Low Saxon **e(e)mt**, **empe** and varieties (Old Saxon **emeta**) and to German **Ameise** (Old High German **āmeiza**).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] All of these words come from West Germanic ***ǣmaitjōn**, and the original meaning of the word was "the biter" (from Proto-Germanic ***ai-**, "off, away" + ***mait-** "cut").
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The family name *Formicidae* is derived from the Latin **formīca** ("ant") from which the words in other Romance languages, such as the Portuguese **formiga**, Italian **formica**, Spanish **hormiga**, Romanian **furnică**, and French **fourmi** are derived.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The study of ants is called *myrmecology*, from Ancient Greek μύρμηξ *mýrmēx* ("ant").
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The family Formicidae belongs to the order Hymenoptera, which also includes sawflies, bees, and wasps.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ants evolved from a lineage within the stinging wasps, and a 2013 study suggests that they are a sister group of the Apoidea.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] However, since Apoidea is a superfamily, ants must be upgraded to the same rank.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] A more detailed basic taxonomy was proposed in 2020.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Three species of the extinct mid-Cretaceous genera *Camelomecia* and *Camelosphecia* were placed outside of the Formicidae, in a separate clade within the general superfamily Formicoidea, which, together with Apoidea, forms the higher-ranking group Formicapoidina.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] (2021) suggest that the common ancestors of ants and apoids within the Formicapoidina probably existed as early as in the end of the Jurassic period, before divergence in the Cretaceous.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Wilson and his colleagues identified the fossil remains of an ant (*Sphecomyrma*) that lived in the Cretaceous period.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The specimen, trapped in amber dating back to around 92 million years ago, has features found in some wasps, but not found in modern ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The oldest fossils of ants date to the mid-Cretaceous, around 113–100 million years ago, which belong to extinct stem-groups such as the Haidomyrmecinae, Sphecomyrminae and Zigrasimeciinae, with modern ant subfamilies appearing towards the end of the Cretaceous around 80–70 million years ago.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ants diversified extensively during the Angiosperm Terrestrial Revolution and assumed ecological dominance around 60 million years ago.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Some groups, such as the Leptanillinae and Martialinae, are suggested to have diversified from early primitive ants that were likely to have been predators underneath the surface of the soil.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] During the Cretaceous period, a few species of primitive ants ranged widely on the Laurasian supercontinent (the Northern Hemisphere).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Their representation in the fossil record is poor, in comparison to the populations of other insects, representing only about 1% of fossil evidence of insects in the era.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ants became dominant after adaptive radiation at the beginning of the Paleogene period.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] By the Oligocene and Miocene, ants had come to represent 20–40% of all insects found in major fossil deposits.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Of the species that lived in the Eocene epoch, around one in 10 genera survive to the present.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Genera surviving today comprise 56% of the genera in Baltic amber fossils (early Oligocene), and 92% of the genera in Dominican amber fossils (apparently early Miocene).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Termites live in colonies and are sometimes called "white ants", but termites are only distantly related to ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] They are the sub-order Isoptera, and together with cockroaches, they form the order Blattodea.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Blattodeans are related to mantids, crickets, and other winged insects that do not undergo complete metamorphosis.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Like ants, termites are eusocial, with sterile workers, but they differ greatly in the genetics of reproduction.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The similarity of their social structure to that of ants is attributed to convergent evolution.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Velvet ants look like large ants, but are wingless female wasps.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] They are found on all continents except Antarctica, and only a few large islands, such as Greenland, Iceland, parts of Polynesia and the Hawaiian Islands lack native ant species.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ants occupy a wide range of ecological niches and exploit many different food resources as direct or indirect herbivores, predators and scavengers.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Most ant species are omnivorous generalists, but a few are specialist feeders.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] There is considerable variation in ant abundance across habitats, peaking in the moist tropics to nearly six times that found in less suitable habitats.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Their ecological dominance has been examined primarily using estimates of their biomass: myrmecologist E.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] More careful estimates made in 2022 which take into account regional variations puts the global ant contribution at 12 megatons of dry carbon, which is about 20% of the total human contribution, but greater than that of the wild birds and mammals combined.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] This study also puts a conservative estimate of the ants at about 20 × 1015 (20 quadrillion).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ants range in size from 0.75 to 52 millimetres (0.030–2.0 in), the largest species being the fossil *Titanomyrma giganteum*, the queen of which was 6 cm (2+1⁄2 in) long with a wingspan of 15 cm (6 in).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ants vary in colour; most ants are yellow to red or brown to black, but a few species are green and some tropical species have a metallic lustre.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] More than 13,800 species are currently known (with upper estimates of the potential existence of about 22,000; see the article List of ant genera), with the greatest diversity in the tropics.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Taxonomic studies continue to resolve the classification and systematics of ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Online databases of ant species, including AntWeb and the Hymenoptera Name Server, help to keep track of the known and newly described species.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The relative ease with which ants may be sampled and studied in ecosystems has made them useful as indicator species in biodiversity studies.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ants are distinct in their morphology from other insects in having geniculate (elbowed) antennae, metapleural glands, and a strong constriction of their second abdominal segment into a node-like petiole.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The body is divided into three distinct sections (formally known as *tagmata*): the head, mesosoma, and metasoma.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The petiole forms a narrow waist between their mesosoma (thorax plus the first abdominal segment, which is fused to it) and gaster (abdomen less the abdominal segments in the petiole).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The petiole may be formed by one or two nodes (the second alone, or the second and third abdominal segments).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Tergosternal fusion, when the tergite and sternite of a segment fuse together, can occur partly or fully on the second, third and fourth abdominal segment and is used in identification.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Fourth abdominal tergosternal fusion was formerly used as character that defined the poneromorph subfamilies, Ponerinae and relatives within their clade, but this is no longer considered a synapomorphic character.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Like other arthropods, ants have an exoskeleton, an external covering that provides a protective casing around the body and a point of attachment for muscles, in contrast to the internal skeletons of humans and other vertebrates.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Insects do not have lungs; oxygen and other gases, such as carbon dioxide, pass through their exoskeleton via tiny valves called spiracles.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Insects also lack closed blood vessels; instead, they have a long, thin, perforated tube along the top of the body (called the "dorsal aorta") that functions like a heart, and pumps haemolymph toward the head, thus driving the circulation of the internal fluids.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The nervous system consists of a ventral nerve cord that runs the length of the body, with several ganglia and branches along the way reaching into the extremities of the appendages.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] An ant's head contains many sensory organs.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Like most insects, ants have compound eyes made from numerous tiny lenses attached together.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ant eyes are good for acute movement detection, but do not offer a high resolution image.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] They also have three small ocelli (simple eyes) on the top of the head that detect light levels and polarization.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Compared to vertebrates, ants tend to have blurrier eyesight, particularly in smaller species, and a few subterranean taxa are completely blind.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] However, some ants, such as Australia's bulldog ant, have excellent vision and are capable of discriminating the distance and size of objects moving nearly a meter away.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Based on experiments conducted to test their ability to differentiate between selected wavelengths of light, some ant species such as *Camponotus blandus, Solenopsis invicta,* and *Formica cunicularia* are thought to possess a degree of colour vision.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Two antennae ("feelers") are attached to the head; these organs detect chemicals, air currents, and vibrations; they also are used to transmit and receive signals through touch.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The head has two strong jaws, the mandibles, used to carry food, manipulate objects, construct nests, and for defence.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] In some species, a small pocket (infrabuccal chamber) inside the mouth stores food, so it may be passed to other ants or their larvae.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Both the wings and the 6 legs of the ant are attached to the mesosoma ("thorax").
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The legs terminate in a hooked claw which allows them to hook on and climb surfaces.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Only reproductive ants (queens and males) have wings.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Queens shed their wings after the nuptial flight, leaving visible stubs, a distinguishing feature of queens.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] In a few species, wingless queens (ergatoids) and males occur.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The metasoma (the "abdomen") of the ant houses important internal organs, including those of the reproductive, respiratory (tracheae), and excretory systems.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Workers of many species have their egg-laying structures modified into stings that are used for subduing prey and defending their nests.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] In the colonies of a few ant species, there are physical castes—workers in distinct size-classes, called minor (micrergates), median, and major ergates (macrergates).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Often, the larger ants have disproportionately larger heads, and correspondingly stronger mandibles.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Although formally known as dinergates, such individuals are sometimes called "soldier" ants because their stronger mandibles make them more effective in fighting, although they still are workers and their "duties" typically do not vary greatly from the minor or median workers.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] In a few species, the median workers are absent, creating a sharp divide between the minors and majors.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Weaver ants, for example, have a distinct bimodal size distribution.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Some other species show continuous variation in the size of workers.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The smallest and largest workers in *Carebara diversa* show nearly a 500-fold difference in their dry weights.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Workers cannot mate; however, because of the haplodiploid sex-determination system in ants, workers of a number of species can lay unfertilised eggs that become fully fertile, haploid males.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The role of workers may change with their age and in some species, such as honeypot ants, young workers are fed until their gasters are distended, and act as living food storage vessels.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] These food storage workers are called *repletes*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] For instance, these replete workers develop in the North American honeypot ant *Myrmecocystus mexicanus*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Usually the largest workers in the colony develop into repletes; and, if repletes are removed from the colony, other workers become repletes, demonstrating the flexibility of this particular polymorphism.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] This polymorphism in morphology and behaviour of workers initially was thought to be determined by environmental factors such as nutrition and hormones that led to different developmental paths; however, genetic differences between worker castes have been noted in *Acromyrmex* sp.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] These polymorphisms are caused by relatively small genetic changes; differences in a single gene of *Solenopsis invicta* can decide whether the colony will have single or multiple queens.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Genome size is a fundamental characteristic of an organism.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ants have been found to have tiny genomes, with the evolution of genome size suggested to occur through loss and accumulation of non-coding regions, mainly transposable elements, and occasionally by whole genome duplication.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] This may be related to colonisation processes, but further studies are needed to verify this.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] If the egg is fertilised, the progeny will be female diploid; if not, it will be male haploid.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ants develop by complete metamorphosis with the larva stages passing through a pupal stage before emerging as an adult.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The larva is largely immobile and is fed and cared for by workers.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Food is given to the larvae by trophallaxis, a process in which an ant regurgitates liquid food held in its crop.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] This is also how adults share food, stored in the "social stomach".
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Larvae, especially in the later stages, may also be provided solid food, such as trophic eggs, pieces of prey, and seeds brought by workers.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The larvae grow through a series of four or five moults and enter the pupal stage.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The pupa has the appendages free and not fused to the body as in a butterfly pupa.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The differentiation into queens and workers (which are both female), and different castes of workers, is influenced in some species by the nutrition the larvae obtain.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Genetic influences and the control of gene expression by the developmental environment are complex and the determination of caste continues to be a subject of research.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Winged male ants, called drones (termed "aner" in old literature), emerge from pupae along with the usually winged breeding females.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Some species, such as army ants, have wingless queens.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Larvae and pupae need to be kept at fairly constant temperatures to ensure proper development, and so often are moved around among the various brood chambers within the colony.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] A new ergate (worker) spends the first few days of its adult life caring for the queen and young.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] She then graduates to digging and other nest work, and later to defending the nest and foraging.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] These changes are sometimes fairly sudden, and define what are called temporal castes.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Such age-based task-specialization or polyethism has been suggested as having evolved due to the high casualties involved in foraging and defence, making it an acceptable risk only for ants who are older and likely to die sooner from natural causes.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] In the Brazilian ant *Forelius pusillus,* the nest entrance is closed from the outside to protect the colony from predatory ant species at sunset each day.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] One to eight workers seal the nest entrance from the outside, in effect sacrificing themselves, as they have no chance of returning to the nest.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Whether these seemingly suicidal workers are older workers has not been determined.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The queens can live for up to 30 years, and workers live from 1 to 3 years.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Males, however, are more transitory, being quite short-lived and surviving for only a few weeks.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ant queens are estimated to live 100 times as long as solitary insects of a similar size.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Ants are active all year long in the tropics; however, in cooler regions, they survive the winter in hibernation.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The forms of inactivity are varied and some temperate species have larvae going into the inactive state (diapause), while in others, the adults alone pass the winter in a state of reduced activity.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] A wide range of reproductive strategies have been noted in ant species.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Females of many species are known to be capable of reproducing asexually through thelytokous parthenogenesis.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Secretions from the male accessory glands in some species can plug the female genital opening and prevent females from re-mating.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Most ant species have a system in which only the queen and breeding females have the ability to mate.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Contrary to popular belief, some ant nests have multiple queens, while others may exist without queens.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Workers with the ability to reproduce are called "gamergates" and colonies that lack queens are then called gamergate colonies; colonies with queens are said to be queen-right.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] In the ant *Cataglyphis hispanica,* workers are produced by hybridization of two distinct lineages while the male and female reproductives are produced through (asexual) parthenogenesis.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The production of hybrid workers with the existence of non-hybrid queens and males has been termed as "social hybridogenesis".
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] This has been noted in the genera *Messor*, *Pogonomyrmex*, *Cataglyphis* and *Solenopsis*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The use of sperm of another species by females has been termed as sperm parasitism.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Queen *M. ibericus* in this region were able to produce *M. structor* males through cloning of sperms stored in their spermatheca and producing hybrid workers by fertilizing her eggs with the cloned sperm.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The hybrid workers have a *M. structor* phenotype with mitochondrial DNA of *M. ibericus*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] This reproductive mode has been termed as "xenoparous", defined by one species being able to produce the offspring of another species.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Drones can enter a foreign colony and mate with existing queens in some species such as in army ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] When the drone is initially attacked by the workers, it releases a mating pheromone.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] If recognized as a mate, it will be carried to the queen to mate.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Males may also patrol the nest and fight others by grabbing them with their mandibles, piercing their exoskeleton and then marking them with a pheromone.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The marked male is interpreted as an invader by worker ants and is killed.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Most ants are univoltine, producing a new generation each year.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] During the species-specific breeding period, winged females and winged males, known to entomologists as alates, leave the colony in what is called a nuptial flight.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The nuptial flight usually takes place in the late spring or early summer when the weather is hot and humid.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Heat makes flying easier, and freshly fallen rain makes the ground softer for mated queens to dig nests.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Males typically take flight before the females.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Males then use visual cues to find a common mating ground, for example, a landmark such as a pine tree to which other males in the area converge.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Males secrete a mating pheromone that females follow.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Males will mount females in the air, but the actual mating process usually takes place on the ground.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Females of some species mate with just one male but in others they may mate with as many as ten or more different males, storing the sperm in their spermathecae.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The genus *Cardiocondyla* have species with both winged and wingless males, where the latter will only mate with females living in the same nest.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Some species in the genus have lost winged males completely, and only produce wingless males.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] In *C. elegans,* workers may transport newly emerged queens to other conspecific nests where the wingless males from unrelated colonies can mate with them, a behavioural adaptation that may reduce the chances of inbreeding.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Mated females then seek a suitable place to begin a colony.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] There, they break off their wings using their tibial spurs and begin to lay and care for eggs.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The females can selectively fertilise future eggs with the sperm stored to produce diploid workers or lay unfertilized haploid eggs to produce drones.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The first workers to hatch, known as nanitics, are weaker and smaller than later workers but they begin to serve the colony immediately.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] They enlarge the nest, forage for food, and care for the other eggs.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Species that have multiple queens may have a queen leaving the nest along with some workers to found a colony at a new site, a process akin to swarming in honeybees.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The typical ant species has a colony occupying a single nest, housing one or more queens, where the brood is raised.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] There are however more than 150 species of ants in 49 genera that are known to have colonies consisting of multiple spatially separated nests.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] These polydomous (as opposed to monodomous) colonies have food and workers moving between the nests.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Membership to a colony is identified by the response of worker ants which identify whether another individual belongs to their own colony or not.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] A signature cocktail of body surface chemicals (also known as cuticular hydrocarbons or CHCs) forms the so-called colony odor which other members can recognize.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Some ant species appear to be less discriminating; in the Argentine ant *Linepithema humile,* workers carried from a colony anywhere in the southern US and Mexico are acceptable within other colonies in the same region.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] Similarly, workers from colonies established in Europe are accepted by any other colonies within Europe, but not by the colonies in the Americas.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p01] The interpretation of these observations has been debated and some have been termed these large populations as supercolonies while others have termed the populations as unicolonial.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ants communicate with each other using pheromones, sounds, and touch.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Since most ants live on the ground, they use the soil surface to leave pheromone trails that may be followed by other ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In species that forage in groups, a forager that finds food marks a trail on the way back to the colony; this trail is followed by other ants, these ants then reinforce the trail when they head back with food to the colony.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] When the food source is exhausted, no new trails are marked by returning ants and the scent slowly dissipates.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] This behaviour helps ants deal with changes in their environment.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] For instance, when an established path to a food source is blocked by an obstacle, the foragers leave the path to explore new routes.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] If an ant is successful, it leaves a new trail marking the shortest route on its return.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Successful trails are followed by more ants, reinforcing better routes and gradually identifying the best path.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ants use pheromones for more than just making trails.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] A crushed ant emits an alarm pheromone that sends nearby ants into an attack frenzy and attracts more ants from farther away.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Several ant species even use "propaganda pheromones" to confuse enemy ants and make them fight among themselves.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Pheromones are produced by a wide range of structures including Dufour's glands, poison glands and glands on the hindgut, pygidium, rectum, sternum, and hind tibia.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Pheromones also are exchanged, mixed with food, and passed by trophallaxis, transferring information within the colony.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] This allows other ants to detect what task group (e.g., foraging or nest maintenance) other colony members belong to.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In ant species with queen castes, when the dominant queen stops producing a specific pheromone, workers begin to raise new queens in the colony.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some ants produce sounds by stridulation, using the gaster segments and their mandibles.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Sounds may be used to communicate with colony members or with other species.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ants attack and defend themselves by biting and, in many species, by stinging often injecting or spraying chemicals.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Bullet ants (*Paraponera*), located in Central and South America, are considered to have the most painful sting of any insect, although it is usually not fatal to humans.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] This sting is given the highest rating on the Schmidt sting pain index.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The sting of jack jumper ants can be lethal for humans, and an antivenom has been developed for it.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Fire ants, *Solenopsis* spp., are unique in having a venom sac containing piperidine alkaloids.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Their stings are painful and can be dangerous to hypersensitive people.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Formicine ants secrete a poison from their glands, made mainly of formic acid.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] *Pseudoneoponera* (formerly *Pachycondyla*) produce a string of foam with bitter-tasting cyclic dipeptides from their venom glands when disturbed.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Trap-jaw ants of the genus *Odontomachus* are equipped with mandibles called trap-jaws, which snap shut faster than any other predatory appendages within the animal kingdom.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] One study of *Odontomachus bauri* recorded peak speeds of between 126 and 230 km/h (78 and 143 mph), with the jaws closing within 130 microseconds on average.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The ants were also observed to use their jaws as a catapult to eject intruders or fling themselves backward to escape a threat.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Before striking, the ant opens its mandibles extremely widely and locks them in this position by an internal mechanism.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Energy is stored in a thick band of muscle and explosively released when triggered by the stimulation of sensory organs resembling hairs on the inside of the mandibles.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The mandibles also permit slow and fine movements for other tasks.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Trap-jaws also are seen in other ponerines such as *Anochetus*, as well as some genera in the tribe Attini, such as *Daceton*, *Orectognathus*, and *Strumigenys*, which are viewed as examples of convergent evolution.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] A Malaysian species of ant in the *Camponotus* *cylindricus* group has enlarged mandibular glands that extend into their gaster.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] A few species of ant feign death (thanatosis) to escape predators usually in lone encounters but one species, *Polyrhachis femorata*, is known to feign death in numbers within their nest.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In addition to defence against predators, ants need to protect their colonies from pathogens.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Secretions from the metapleural gland, unique to the ants, produce a complex range of chemicals including several with antibiotic properties.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some worker ants maintain the hygiene of the colony and their activities include undertaking or *necrophoresis*, the disposal of dead nest-mates.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In *Megaponera analis,* injured ants are treated by nest-mates with secretions from their metapleural glands which protect them from infection.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] *Camponotus* ants do not have a metapleural gland and *Camponotus maculatus* as well as *C. floridanus* workers have been found to amputate the affected legs of nestmates when the femur is injured.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] A femur injury carries a greater risk of infection unlike a tibia injury.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Nests may be protected from physical threats such as flooding and overheating by elaborate nest architecture.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Workers of *Cataulacus muticus*, an arboreal species that lives in plant hollows, respond to flooding by drinking water inside the nest, and excreting it outside.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] *Camponotus anderseni*, which nests in the cavities of wood in mangrove habitats, deals with submergence under water by switching to anaerobic respiration.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Many animals can learn behaviours by imitation, but ants may be the only group apart from mammals where interactive teaching has been observed.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] A knowledgeable forager of *Temnothorax albipennis* can lead a naïve nest-mate to newly discovered food by the process of tandem running.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The follower obtains knowledge through its leading tutor.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The leader is acutely sensitive to the progress of the follower and slows down when the follower lags and speeds up when the follower gets too close.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Controlled experiments with colonies of *Cerapachys biroi* suggest that an individual may choose nest roles based on her previous experience.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] An entire generation of identical workers was divided into two groups whose outcome in food foraging was controlled.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] One group was continually rewarded with prey, while it was made certain that the other failed.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] As a result, members of the successful group intensified their foraging attempts while the unsuccessful group ventured out fewer and fewer times.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] A month later, the successful foragers continued in their role while the others had moved to specialise in brood care.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Complex nests are built by many ant species, but other species are nomadic and do not build permanent structures.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ants may form subterranean nests or build them on trees.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] These nests may be found in the ground, under stones or logs, inside logs, hollow stems, or even acorns.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The materials used for construction include soil and plant matter, and ants carefully select their nest sites; *Temnothorax albipennis* will avoid sites with dead ants, as these may indicate the presence of pests or disease.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] They are quick to abandon established nests at the first sign of threats.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The army ants of South America, such as the *Eciton burchellii* species, and the driver ants of Africa do not build permanent nests, but instead, alternate between nomadism and stages where the workers form a temporary nest (bivouac) from their own bodies, by holding each other together.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Weaver ant (*Oecophylla* spp.) workers build nests in trees by attaching leaves together, first pulling them together with bridges of workers and then inducing their larvae to produce silk as they are moved along the leaf edges.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Similar forms of nest construction are seen in some species of *Polyrhachis*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some ant species, such as those that use natural cavities, can be opportunistic and make use of the controlled micro-climate provided inside human dwellings and other artificial structures to house their colonies and nest structures.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Most ants are generalist predators, scavengers, and indirect herbivores, but a few have evolved specialised ways of obtaining nutrition.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] It is believed that many ant species that engage in indirect herbivory rely on specialized symbiosis with their gut microbes to upgrade the nutritional value of the food they collect and allow them to survive in nitrogen poor regions, such as rainforest canopies.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Leafcutter ants (*Atta* and *Acromyrmex*) feed exclusively on a fungus that grows only within their colonies.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] They continually collect leaves which are taken to the colony, cut into tiny pieces and placed in fungal gardens.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ergates specialise in related tasks according to their sizes.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The largest ants cut stalks, smaller workers chew the leaves and the smallest tend the fungus.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Leafcutter ants are sensitive enough to recognise the reaction of the fungus to different plant material, apparently detecting chemical signals from the fungus.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] If a particular type of leaf is found to be toxic to the fungus, the colony will no longer collect it.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The ants feed on structures produced by the fungi called *gongylidia*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Symbiotic bacteria on the exterior surface of the ants produce antibiotics that kill bacteria introduced into the nest that may harm the fungi.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Foraging ants travel distances of up to 200 metres (700 ft) from their nest and scent trails allow them to find their way back even in the dark.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In hot and arid regions, day-foraging ants face death by desiccation, so the ability to find the shortest route back to the nest reduces that risk.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Diurnal desert ants of the genus *Cataglyphis* such as the Sahara desert ant navigate by keeping track of direction as well as distance travelled.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Distances travelled are measured using an internal pedometer that keeps count of the steps taken and also by evaluating the movement of objects in their visual field (optical flow).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Directions are measured using the position of the sun.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] They integrate this information to find the shortest route back to their nest.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Like all ants, they can also make use of visual landmarks when available as well as olfactory and tactile cues to navigate.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some species of ant are able to use the Earth's magnetic field for navigation.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The compound eyes of ants have specialised cells that detect polarised light from the Sun, which is used to determine direction.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] These polarization detectors are sensitive in the ultraviolet region of the light spectrum.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In some army ant species, a group of foragers who become separated from the main column may sometimes turn back on themselves and form a circular ant mill.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The workers may then run around continuously until they die of exhaustion.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The female worker ants do not have wings and reproductive females lose their wings after their mating flights in order to begin their colonies.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Therefore, unlike their wasp ancestors, most ants travel by walking.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] For example, Jerdon's jumping ant (*Harpegnathos saltator*) is able to jump by synchronising the action of its mid and hind pairs of legs.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] There are several species of gliding ant including *Cephalotes atratus*; this may be a common trait among arboreal ants with small colonies.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ants with this ability are able to control their horizontal movement so as to catch tree trunks when they fall from atop the forest canopy.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Other species of ants can form chains to bridge gaps over water, underground, or through spaces in vegetation.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some species also form floating rafts that help them survive floods.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] These rafts may also have a role in allowing ants to colonise islands.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] *Polyrhachis sokolova*, a species of ant found in Australian mangrove swamps, can swim and live in underwater nests.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Since they lack gills, they go to trapped pockets of air in the submerged nests to breathe.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Not all ants have the same kind of societies.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The Australian bulldog ants are among the biggest and most basal of ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Like virtually all ants, they are eusocial, but their social behaviour is poorly developed compared to other species.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Each individual hunts alone, using her large eyes instead of chemical senses to find prey.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some species attack and take over neighbouring ant colonies.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Extreme specialists among these slave-raiding ants, such as the Amazon ants, are incapable of feeding themselves and need captured workers to survive.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Captured workers of enslaved *Temnothorax* species have evolved a counter-strategy, destroying just the female pupae of the slave-making *Temnothorax americanus*, but sparing the males (who do not take part in slave-raiding as adults).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ants identify kin and nestmates through their scent, which comes from hydrocarbon-laced secretions that coat their exoskeletons.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] If an ant is separated from its original colony, it will eventually lose the colony scent.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Any ant that enters a colony without a matching scent will be attacked.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Parasitic ant species enter the colonies of host ants and establish themselves as social parasites; species such as *Strumigenys xenos* are entirely parasitic and do not have workers, but instead, rely on the food gathered by their *Strumigenys perplexa* hosts.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] This form of parasitism is seen across many ant genera, but the parasitic ant is usually a species that is closely related to its host.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] A variety of methods are employed to enter the nest of the host ant.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] A parasitic queen may enter the host nest before the first brood has hatched, establishing herself prior to development of a colony scent.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Other species use pheromones to confuse the host ants or to trick them into carrying the parasitic queen into the nest.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some simply fight their way into the nest.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] A conflict between the sexes of a species is seen in some species of ants with these reproducers apparently competing to produce offspring that are as closely related to them as possible.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The most extreme form involves the production of clonal offspring.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] An extreme of sexual conflict is seen in *Wasmannia auropunctata*, where the queens produce diploid daughters by thelytokous parthenogenesis and males produce clones by a process whereby a diploid egg loses its maternal contribution to produce haploid males who are clones of the father.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ants form symbiotic associations with a range of species, including other ant species, other insects, plants, and fungi.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] They also are preyed on by many animals and even certain fungi.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some arthropod species spend part of their lives within ant nests, either preying on ants, their larvae, and eggs, consuming the food stores of the ants, or avoiding predators.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] These inquilines may bear a close resemblance to ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The nature of this ant mimicry (myrmecomorphy) varies, with some cases involving Batesian mimicry, where the mimic reduces the risk of predation.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Others show Wasmannian mimicry, a form of mimicry seen only in inquilines.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Aphids and other hemipteran insects secrete a sweet liquid called honeydew, when they feed on plant sap.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The sugars in honeydew are a high-energy food source, which many ant species collect.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In some cases, the aphids secrete the honeydew in response to ants tapping them with their antennae.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The ants in turn keep predators away from the aphids and will move them from one feeding location to another.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] When migrating to a new area, many colonies will take the aphids with them, to ensure a continued supply of honeydew.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ants also tend mealybugs to harvest their honeydew.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Mealybugs may become a serious pest of pineapples if ants are present to protect mealybugs from their natural enemies.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Myrmecophilous (ant-loving) caterpillars of the butterfly family Lycaenidae (e.g., blues, coppers, or hairstreaks) are herded by the ants, led to feeding areas in the daytime, and brought inside the ants' nest at night.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The caterpillars have a gland which secretes honeydew when the ants massage them.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The chemicals in the secretions of *Arhopala japonica* alter the behavior of attendant *Pristomyrmex punctatus* workers, making them less aggressive and stationary.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The relationship, formerly characterized as "mutualistic", is now considered as possibly a case of the ants being parasitically manipulated by the caterpillars.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some caterpillars produce vibrations and sounds that are perceived by the ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] A similar adaptation can be seen in grizzled skipper butterflies that emit vibrations by expanding their wings in order to communicate with ants, which are natural predators of these butterflies.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Other caterpillars have evolved from ant-loving to ant-eating: these myrmecophagous caterpillars secrete a pheromone that makes the ants act as if the caterpillar is one of their own larvae.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The caterpillar is then taken into the ant nest where it feeds on the ant larvae.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] A number of specialized bacteria have been found as endosymbionts in ant guts.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some of the dominant bacteria belong to the order Hyphomicrobiales whose members are known for being nitrogen-fixing symbionts in legumes but the species found in ant lack the ability to fix nitrogen.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Fungus-growing ants that make up the tribe Attini, including leafcutter ants, cultivate certain species of fungus in the genera *Leucoagaricus* or *Leucocoprinus* of the family Agaricaceae.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In this ant-fungus mutualism, both species depend on each other for survival.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The ant *Allomerus decemarticulatus* has evolved a three-way association with the host plant, *Hirtella physophora* (Chrysobalanaceae), and a sticky fungus which is used to trap their insect prey.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Lemon ants make devil's gardens by killing surrounding plants with their stings and leaving a pure patch of lemon ant trees, (*Duroia hirsuta*).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] This modification of the forest provides the ants with more nesting sites inside the stems of the *Duroia* trees.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Although some ants obtain nectar from flowers, pollination by ants is somewhat rare, one example being of the pollination of the orchid *Leporella fimbriata* which induces male *Myrmecia urens* to pseudocopulate with the flowers, transferring pollen in the process.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] One theory that has been proposed for the rarity of pollination is that the secretions of the metapleural gland inactivate and reduce the viability of pollen.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some plants, mostly angiosperms but also some ferns, have special nectar exuding structures, extrafloral nectaries, that provide food for ants, which in turn protect the plant from more damaging herbivorous insects.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Species such as the bullhorn acacia (*Acacia cornigera*) in Central America have hollow thorns that house colonies of stinging ants (*Pseudomyrmex ferruginea*) who defend the tree against insects, browsing mammals, and epiphytic vines.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Isotopic labelling studies suggest that plants also obtain nitrogen from the ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In return, the ants obtain food from protein- and lipid-rich Beltian bodies.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In Fiji *Philidris nagasau* (Dolichoderinae) are known to selectively grow species of epiphytic *Squamellaria* (Rubiaceae) which produce large domatia inside which the ant colonies nest.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The ants plant the seeds and the domatia of young seedling are immediately occupied and the ant faeces in them contribute to rapid growth.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Similar dispersal associations are found with other dolichoderines in the region as well.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Another example of this type of ectosymbiosis comes from the *Macaranga* tree, which has stems adapted to house colonies of *Crematogaster* ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Many plant species have seeds that are adapted for dispersal by ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Seed dispersal by ants or myrmecochory is widespread, and new estimates suggest that nearly 9% of all plant species may have such ant associations.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Often, seed-dispersing ants perform directed dispersal, depositing the seeds in locations that increase the likelihood of seed survival to reproduction.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some plants in arid, fire-prone systems are particularly dependent on ants for their survival and dispersal as the seeds are transported to safety below the ground.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Many ant-dispersed seeds have special external structures, elaiosomes, that are sought after by ants as food.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ants can substantially alter rate of decomposition and nutrient cycling in their nest.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] By myrmecochory and modification of soil conditions they substantially alter vegetation and nutrient cycling in surrounding ecosystem.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] A convergence, possibly a form of mimicry, is seen in the eggs of stick insects.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] They have an edible elaiosome-like structure and are taken into the ant nest where the young hatch.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Most ants are predatory and some prey on and obtain food from other social insects including other ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some species specialise in preying on termites (*Megaponera* and *Neoponera*) while a few Cerapachyinae prey on other ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some termites, including *Nasutitermes corniger*, form associations with certain ant species to keep away predatory ant species.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The tropical wasp *Mischocyttarus drewseni* coats the pedicel of its nest with an ant-repellent chemical.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] It is suggested that many tropical wasps may build their nests in trees and cover them to protect themselves from ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Other wasps, such as *A. multipicta*, defend against ants by blasting them off the nest with bursts of wing buzzing.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Stingless bees (*Trigona* and *Melipona*) use chemical defences against ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Flies in the Old World genus *Bengalia* (Calliphoridae) prey on ants and are kleptoparasites, snatching prey or brood from the mandibles of adult ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Wingless and legless females of the Malaysian phorid fly (*Vestigipoda myrmolarvoidea*) live in the nests of ants of the genus *Aenictus* and are cared for by the ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Fungi in the genera *Cordyceps* and *Ophiocordyceps* infect ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ants react to their infection by climbing up plants and sinking their mandibles into plant tissue.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The fungus kills the ants, grows on their remains, and produces a fruiting body.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] It appears that the fungus alters the behaviour of the ant to help disperse its spores in a microhabitat that best suits the fungus.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Strepsipteran parasites also manipulate their ant host to climb grass stems, to help the parasite find mates.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] A nematode (*Myrmeconema neotropicum*) that infects canopy ants (*Cephalotes atratus*) causes the black-coloured gasters of workers to turn red.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The parasite also alters the behaviour of the ant, causing them to carry their gasters high.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The conspicuous red gasters are mistaken by birds for ripe fruits, such as *Hyeronima alchorneoides*, and eaten.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The droppings of the bird are collected by other ants and fed to their young, leading to further spread of the nematode.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] South American poison dart frogs in the genus *Dendrobates* feed mainly on ants, and the toxins in the skin of some species come from the ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Formicine ants in the genera *Brachymyrmex* and *Paratrechina* have been found to contain pumiliotoxin found in *Dendrobates pumilio*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The West African frog *Phrynomantis microps* is able to move within the nests of *Paltothyreus tarsatus* ants, producing peptides on its skin that prevent the ants from stinging them.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Army ants forage in a wide roving column, attacking any animals in that path that are unable to escape.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In Central and South America, *Eciton burchellii* is the swarming ant most commonly attended by "ant-following" birds such as antbirds and woodcreepers.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] This behaviour was once considered mutualistic, but later studies found the birds to be parasitic.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Direct kleptoparasitism (birds stealing food from the ants' grasp) is rare and has been noted in Inca doves which pick seeds at nest entrances as they are being transported by species of *Pogonomyrmex*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Birds that follow ants eat many prey insects and thus decrease the foraging success of ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Birds indulge in a peculiar behaviour called anting that, as yet, is not fully understood.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Here birds rest on ant nests, or pick and drop ants onto their wings and feathers; this may be a means to remove ectoparasites from the birds.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Anteaters, aardvarks, pangolins, echidnas and numbats have special adaptations for living on a diet of ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] These adaptations include long, sticky tongues to capture ants and strong claws to break into ant nests.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Brown bears (*Ursus arctos*) have been found to feed on ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] About 12%, 16%, and 4% of their faecal volume in spring, summer and autumn, respectively, is composed of ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ants perform many ecological roles that are beneficial to humans, including the suppression of pest populations and aeration of the soil.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] It has been estimated that an average of about 1.5 tons of subsoil are moved to the surface (bioturbation) by ants per year per hectare.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The use of weaver ants in citrus cultivation in southern China is considered one of the oldest known applications of biological control.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] On the other hand, ants may become nuisances when they invade buildings or cause economic losses.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In some parts of the world (mainly Africa and South America), large ants, especially army ants, are used as surgical sutures.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The wound is pressed together and ants are applied along it.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The ant seizes the edges of the wound in its mandibles and locks in place.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The body is then cut off and the head and mandibles remain in place to close the wound.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The large heads of the dinergates (soldiers) of the leafcutting ant *Atta cephalotes* are also used by native surgeons in closing wounds.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some ants have toxic venom and are of medical importance.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The species include *Paraponera clavata* (tocandira) and *Dinoponera* spp.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] (false tocandiras) of South America and the *Myrmecia* ants of Australia.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In South Africa, ants are used to help harvest the seeds of rooibos (*Aspalathus linearis*), a plant used to make a herbal tea.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The plant disperses its seeds widely, making manual collection difficult.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Black ants collect and store these and other seeds in their nest, where humans can gather them *en masse*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Up to half a pound (200 g) of seeds may be collected from one ant-heap.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Although most ants survive attempts by humans to eradicate them, a few are highly endangered.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] These tend to be island species that have evolved specialized traits and risk being displaced by introduced ant species.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Examples include the critically endangered Sri Lankan relict ant (*Aneuretus simoni*) and *Adetomyrma venatrix* of Madagascar.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ants and their larvae are eaten in different parts of the world.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The eggs of two species of ants are used in Mexican *escamoles*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] They are considered a form of insect caviar and can sell for as much as US$50 per kg going up to US$200 per kg (as of 2006) because they are seasonal and hard to find.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In the Colombian department of Santander, *hormigas culonas* (roughly interpreted as "large-bottomed ants") *Atta laevigata* are toasted alive and eaten.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In areas of India, and throughout Burma and Thailand, a paste of the green weaver ant (*Oecophylla smaragdina*) is served as a condiment with curry.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Weaver ant eggs and larvae, as well as the ants, may be used in a Thai salad, *yam* (Thai: ยำ), in a dish called *yam khai mot daeng* (Thai: ยำไข่มดแดง) or red ant egg salad, a dish that comes from the Issan or north-eastern region of Thailand.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Saville-Kent, in the *Naturalist in Australia* wrote "Beauty, in the case of the green ant, is more than skin-deep.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Their attractive, almost sweetmeat-like translucency possibly invited the first essays at their consumption by the human species".
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Mashed up in water, after the manner of lemon squash, "these ants form a pleasant acid drink which is held in high favor by the natives of North Queensland, and is even appreciated by many European palates".
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ants or their pupae are used as starters for yogurt making in parts of Bulgaria and Turkey.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In his *First Summer in the Sierra*, John Muir notes that the Digger Indians of California ate the tickling, acid gasters of the large jet-black carpenter ants.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The Mexican Indians eat the repletes, or living honey-pots, of the honey ant (*Myrmecocystus*).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some ant species are considered as pests, primarily those that occur in human habitations, where their presence is often problematic.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] For example, the presence of ants would be undesirable in sterile places such as hospitals or kitchens.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some species or genera commonly categorized as pests include the Argentine ant, immigrant pavement ant, yellow crazy ant, banded sugar ant, pharaoh ant, red wood ant, black carpenter ant, odorous house ant, red imported fire ant, and European fire ant.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some ants will raid stored food, some will seek water sources, others may damage indoor structures, some may damage agricultural crops directly or by aiding sucking pests.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The adaptive nature of ant colonies make it nearly impossible to eliminate entire colonies and most pest management practices aim to control local populations and tend to be temporary solutions.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ant populations are managed by a combination of approaches that make use of chemical, biological, and physical methods.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Chemical methods include the use of insecticidal bait which is gathered by ants as food and brought back to the nest where the poison is inadvertently spread to other colony members through trophallaxis.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Management is based on the species and techniques may vary according to the location and circumstance.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Observed by humans since the dawn of history, the behaviour of ants has been documented and the subject of early writings and fables passed from one century to another.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Those using scientific methods, myrmecologists, study ants in the laboratory and in their natural conditions.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Their complex and variable social structures have made ants ideal model organisms.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ultraviolet vision was first discovered in ants by Sir John Lubbock in 1881.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Studies on ants have tested hypotheses in ecology and sociobiology, and have been particularly important in examining the predictions of theories of kin selection and evolutionarily stable strategies.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ant colonies may be studied by rearing or temporarily maintaining them in *formicaria*, specially constructed glass framed enclosures.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Individuals may be tracked for study by marking them with dots of colours.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The successful techniques used by ant colonies have been studied in computer science and robotics to produce distributed and fault-tolerant systems for solving problems, for example Ant colony optimization and Ant robotics.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] This area of biomimetics has led to studies of ant locomotion, search engines that make use of "foraging trails", fault-tolerant storage, and networking algorithms.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] From the late 1950s through the late 1970s, ant farms were popular educational children's toys in the United States.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some later commercial versions use transparent gel instead of soil, allowing greater visibility at the cost of stressing the ants with unnatural light.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Anthropomorphised ants have often been used in fables, children's stories, and religious texts to represent industriousness and cooperative effort, such as in the Aesop fable The Ant and the Grasshopper.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In the Quran, Sulayman is said to have heard and understood an ant warning other ants to return home to avoid being accidentally crushed by Sulayman and his marching army.[Quran 27:18], In parts of Africa, ants are considered to be the messengers of the deities.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some Native American mythology, such as the Hopi mythology, considers ants as the first animals.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ant bites are often said to have curative properties.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The sting of some species of *Pseudomyrmex* is claimed to give fever relief.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ant bites are used in the initiation ceremonies of some Amazon Indian cultures as a test of endurance.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In Greek mythology, the goddess Athena turned the maiden Myrmex into an ant when the latter claimed to have invented the plough, when in fact it was Athena's own invention.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Ant society has always fascinated humans and has been written about both humorously and seriously.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Mark Twain wrote about ants in his 1880 book *A Tramp Abroad*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Some modern authors have used the example of the ants to comment on the relationship between society and the individual.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Examples are Robert Frost in his poem "Departmental" and T.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] White in his fantasy novel *The Once and Future King*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] The plot in French entomologist and writer Bernard Werber's *Les Fourmis* science-fiction trilogy is divided between the worlds of ants and humans; ants and their behaviour are described using contemporary scientific knowledge.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In more recent times, animated cartoons and 3-D animated films featuring ants have been produced including *Antz*, *A Bug's Life*, *The Ant Bully*, *The Ant and the Aardvark*, *Ferdy the Ant* and *Atom Ant.* Renowned myrmecologist E.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] Wilson wrote a short story, "Trailhead" in 2010 for *The New Yorker* magazine, which describes the life and death of an ant-queen and the rise and fall of her colony, from an ants' point of view.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In computer strategy games, ant-based species often benefit from increased production rates due to their single-minded focus, such as the Klackons in the *Master of Orion* series of games or the ChCht in *Deadlock II*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] These characters are often credited with a hive mind, a common misconception about ant colonies.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ant-p02] In the early 1990s, the video game *SimAnt*, which simulated an ant colony, won the 1992 Codie award for "Best Simulation Program".
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ants-climbing-a-tree] To make the "ants", meat is marinated for a short time at room temperature while the noodles are soaked to soften.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ants-climbing-a-tree] In a wok, oil is heated until almost smoking.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ants-climbing-a-tree] The scallions, garlic, and ginger are cooked slightly in the wok before the marinated meat is added.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ants-climbing-a-tree] The softened noodles are added to the wok to soak up the flavor and juices.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ants-climbing-a-tree] Dry noodles that have not yet been softened can also be fried in hot oil to add texture to the dish.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ants-climbing-a-tree] The noodles will puff immediately and can be removed with a bamboo or stainless wire skimmer, then set on paper towels to drain before adding to the rest of the dish.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ants-on-a-log] Stuffed celery became a popular snack in the early 1900s after the inclusion of such recipes as Celery with Roquefort in the book *Catering for Special Occasions with Menus and Recipes* by Fannie Merritt Farmer.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ants-on-a-log] Celery was most commonly stuffed with a form of cheese, the most popular being cream cheese, and was often topped with capers or olives.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ants-on-a-log] The inventor of the peanut butter/raisin combination of the snack is unknown.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ants-on-a-log] However, many attribute the popularization of the combination to the Girl Scouts, where the recipe has been featured in several iterations of the *Girl Scout Cookbook* as far back as 1946, although at that time the recipe was titled "Celery Sticks" and did not include raisins.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/ants-on-a-log] The first time the "Ants on a Log" snack was mentioned in print was in an article published by the *Star Tribune* on February 15, 1959, which reads, "Anne Marie is working on snacks.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] The noodles are known as *bakmi* in Indonesia, where they have been adapted to more closely align with the local tastes and into Javanese and Indo cuisine.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] *Bakmi* are between Chinese-style wheat noodles and Japanese udon in thickness, and there are several variants in Indonesia.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] The name *bakmi* literally translates to "meat noodle".
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] In Indonesia, especially in large urban areas such as Jakarta, Medan, and Surabaya, there are many *warung* food stalls, restaurants, and eateries that serve this type of noodle dish, each specialising in different ingredients and toppings.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] Chinese influence is evident in Indonesian food such as *bakmi*, *mie ayam*, *pangsit*, *mie goreng*, and *kwetiau goreng*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] The words *mie* and *bami*, used in Dutch, come from *bakmi* and were introduced into the Dutch language during the Dutch colonial period in Indonesia.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] Indonesian food is very popular in the Netherlands, and *bami goreng* (fried *bakmi*) is a popular dish.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] In Thailand, wheat-based egg noodles are known as *bami*, which may be ordered as *bami nam* or *bami haeng* (egg noodles with soup and without soup respectively), and the noodles may be used in Chinese style stir-fried dishes.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] In the Philippines, a similar noodle dish is called pancit bam-i or pancit mami, where it is called *bam-i* in Cebuano Bisaya, or *mami/bami* in Tagalog (Filipino).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] The most common recipe of *bakmi* dish in Indonesia uses chicken meat as the majority of Indonesians are Muslims.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] Chicken noodle (Indonesian: *bakmie ayam or mie ayam*), *mie ayam* is wheat noodle topped with diced chicken meat seasoned in soy sauce.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] *Mie ayam* often accompanied with wonton (Indonesian: *pangsit*) either crispy fried or in soup, and also *bakso* (meatball).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] *Bakmi ayam* is a popular Chinese Indonesian dish and ubiquitous in Indonesian cities, it can be served in a restaurant to a humble travelling cart.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] The other popular Indonesian *bakmi* recipe is fried *bakmi* (Indonesian: *bakmie goreng* or Indonesian: *mie goreng*).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] In Indonesia, the most common toppings are diced seasoned chicken with choy sum and fried wonton skin, to a more complete version served with fried or boiled wonton and *bakso* (meatballs).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] The soup is served in a different bowl, and is added to the noodles by the individual diner according to taste.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] Several notable Indonesian dishes developed from the original Chinese wheat noodle tradition includes *mie ayam* (chicken noodle) and *mie goreng* (stir fried noodle in sweet soy sauce).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/bakmi] *I fu mie* is *bakmi* that is first deep fried and then topped with a thickened gravy of vegetables and meat.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] The name *banmian* ('board noodle' or 'block noodle') came from the Hakka method of cutting the noodles into straight strands using a wooden block as ruler.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] In Hakka, some might call it *man-foon-char-guo* (麵粉茶粿) or *dao-ma-chet* (刀嬤切).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] In Hokkien, it was called *mee-hoon-kueh* (麵粉粿; lit.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] 'wheat snack') but what can be found at hawker stalls is generally called *banmian*.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] The current style is a mix between the traditional methods of Hakka and Hokkien.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] The Hakka initially made the noodle by shaving pieces off a block of dough, commonly made from flour (sometimes egg is added for more flavor), while the Hokkien would roll the dough into a large, flat piece that would then be torn by hand into bite-sized bits.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] Traditionally, the dough is hand-kneaded and torn into smaller pieces of dough (about 5 cm or 2 in).
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] The dough can also be kneaded using the machine into a variety of shapes, the most common shape being flat strips of noodle.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] Banmian is common in China, Malaysia, Singapore and Taiwan.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] It consists of egg noodles served in a flavorful soup, often with meat or fish, vegetables and spices.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] Dried anchovies, minced pork, mushrooms, and a leafy vegetable such as sweet potato leaves or sayur manis (*Sauropus androgynus*) are also possible ingredients.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] Traditional versions of banmian use egg noodles that are simply a blend of egg, flour, water and salt that is kneaded and then formed into noodles.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] However, modern banmian is frequently made with a pasta maker which cuts noodles in all sizes.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] The base of the soup can be water, but is more commonly a type of fish stock.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] Normal fish stock can be used, but anchovy stock is a common choice.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] Various ingredients such as onions, garlic, ginger and bean paste can be added to the stock to provide more flavor, although some preparations are so simple that nothing more than plain stock is used.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] In Malaysia, dry noodles and soup are served separately.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] Dry chilli pan mee is a variant which was invented in Chow Kit, Kuala Lumpur, and is often seen in the Klang Valley.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] This dry noodle is served with minced pork, fried onions, anchovies, and topped with a poached egg which is later stirred into the noodles.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] It is usually served with dry chilli or sambal.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] Two common ingredients that are often found across different versions of banmian are mushrooms and anchovies.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] The exact type of each might vary, but they are generally added to the stock base.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] The mushrooms can be dried and are reconstituted in the broth, while the anchovies may be fried until crispy and then served on top of the soup.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] The anchovies also can be added to the stock for flavor and allowed to break down during cooking.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] Once the base stock is completed, nearly anything can be added to complete the banmian.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] This includes vegetables such as green onions, spinach, cabbage and bamboo shoots.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] Vinegar is usually added, occasionally with sugar, to balance the flavor.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] Restaurants may offer fried minced pork or chunks of white fish as a protein-rich addition.
[src:ants-climbing-a-tree/banmian] Finally, an egg is cracked into the hot broth and allowed to cook until the white is set and the yolk is warmed through.
